article.description:
Lisa Leslie, returning from a one-game
absence because of the flu, had 23 points and nine rebounds as the
Los Angeles Sparks defeated the Minnesota Lynx 73-64 Friday night.
article.headline: Leslie has 23 points and nine rebounds in return
article.linkText: Leslie returns from flu to lead Sparks over Lynx
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Sparks continued their
winning ways at home and over Minnesota, but Friday night's
performance didn't satisfy high-scoring Lisa Leslie.

	   "I thought we did a good job of holding it together at the
end,'' said Leslie, who scored 23 points and pulled down a
game-high equaling nine rebounds after a one-game absence.
"However, we didn't play 40 minutes of Sparks basketball. We
didn't have as good of a team effort defensively 40 minutes as we
would have liked.''

	   The Sparks trailed at halftime and were only a single point
ahead with 3:15 to play. But they held on for a 73-64 victory over
the Lynx before a Staples Center crowd announced at 9,112.

	   Tamecka Dixon, DeLisha Milton and reserve Latasha Byears each
added 12 points for the Sparks (9-1), who have won six consecutive
games, a WNBA league-record 26 consecutive home games and 11
straight over the Lynx.

	   Katie Smith scored a season-high 27 for Minnesota (4-6). Her
previous season high was 23 at Sacramento June 1. Smith set the
WNBA single-game scoring record of 46 at Los Angeles on July 8.

	   "We gave it a good shot, but missed some big shots down the
stretch,'' Smith said. "I missed two easy shots and had some
turnovers ... minus those big plays, we might have had a different
result.''

	   Smith's 12 points helped the Lynx to a 31-29 halftime lead.
There were 10 lead changes and three ties in the first half.

	   Svetlana Abrosimova added 10 for the Lynx.

	   Smith's 3-point basket with 52.6 seconds left cut the Sparks'
lead to 68-64, but Minnesota's comeback hopes were thwarted when
Tamika Williams missed two free throws with 28.6 seconds remaining.
Los Angeles sealed the victory when Dixon made one free throw and
Leslie four in the final 26 seconds.

	   "We just couldn't covert in the last few minutes,'' Lynx coach
Brian Agler said. "I thought we had a good control of the game,
but when you play a team like L.A., you can't have a letdown.''

	   Trailing 39-35 with 15:33 to play, the Sparks took the lead for
good with 10-0 run, concluded by Mwadi Mabika's 3-point basket with
13:45 left.

	   Minnesota scored seven straight points, capped by Abrosimova's
3-point basket, to cut the lead to 55-54 with 7:11 remaining. After
an exchange of 5-0 runs which had Los Angeles lead 60-59 with 3:15
left, Leslie's layup, two free throws and Milton's basket gave the
Sparks a 66-59 advantage with 1:37 to play.

	   The Lynx made 23 of 57 shots (40.4 percent), while the Sparks
made 24 of 63 (38.1 percent). Los Angeles made 21 of 27 free throws
(77.8 percent), Minnesota 10 of 15 (66.7 percent). The Sparks led
in rebounds, 31-30.

	   Following a loss in the first meeting between the teams on June
24, 1999, the Sparks have defeated Minnesota 11 consecutive times.
